        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Experimental boundary conditions must be documented with calibrated instrumentation. CFD boundary conditions must be set to match experimental values within the stated measurement uncertainty. Temperature and fluid property consistency must be verified.",
        "threshold": "CFD boundary conditions within ±2% of documented experimental values; fluid properties matched at test temperature"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed for pressure rise (MAE 4.2%), NIH (within 15% at all operating points), and velocity field (RMS error 6.8%). Comparison metrics are defined a priori in the V&V plan. All comparisons include propagated experimental and numerical uncertainty bounds. The comparison norm is consistent with the intended use of identifying worst-case hemolysis conditions.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/oc-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Quantitative comparison metrics must be defined a priori. Pressure rise MAE must be below 10%. NIH predictions must be within 20% of measured values at all validation operating points. Velocity RMS error must be below 12% of peak velocity.",
        "threshold": "Pressure rise MAE < 10%; NIH error < 20%; velocity RMS < 12% of peak"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH) compared against a predicate device. These quantities directly map to the clinical endpoint (patient hemolysis) and the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1). The hemolysis power-law scalar transport model directly computes the QoI used in the decision, with no intermediate transformation that could introduce relevance gaps.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/rqi-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "The QoI used in validation must be the same quantity (or a directly traceable surrogate) as the QoI used in the device assessment decision. The mapping from validated QoI to decision QoI must be documented with no unquantified transformation uncertainty.",
        "threshold": "Direct correspondence between validated NIH and decision RH criterion; transformation uncertainty < 5%"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Validation activities used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same device class and flow regime as the COU device. Operating conditions in validation (2–6 L/min, 2000–3000 RPM) overlap substantially with the COU operating envelope. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water mixture) was used in PIV experiments; NIH experiments used porcine blood. The relevance gap from blood analog use is acknowledged and bounded by the uncertainty quantification on velocity comparisons.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/rva-ac-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Validation geometry must be the same device class (centrifugal blood pump) as the COU device. At least 80% of validation operating points must fall within the COU operating envelope. Any fluid substitution (blood analog) must be documented with a relevance assessment.",
        "threshold": "Same device class; ≥80% operating point overlap with COU envelope; fluid substitution documented"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Numerical solver error' factor as defined in certain NASA-centric V&V frameworks addresses round-off, floating-point accumulation, and iterative convergence residuals in custom or research-grade solvers where the solver internals are accessible for audit. In this assessment, ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 is a commercial, third-party validated solver that has undergone independent numerical verification by the vendor under ISO 9001 quality management. The solver qualification record (QR-FLUENT-2023R1-v4) documents iterative convergence to residuals below 1×10⁻⁶ for all equations, and double-precision arithmetic is confirmed in the solver settings. Numerical solver error as a distinct factor is therefore subsumed entirely within the 'Software quality assurance' and 'Numerical code verification' factors already assessed in this package, which together satisfy the intent of this factor at MRL 2. Treating it as a separate assessable factor would constitute double-counting without adding evidentiary value. This determination is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 guidance that factors may be scoped out when their evidentiary content is fully captured by other assessed factors and the model risk level does not mandate independent treatment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Use error' factor addresses risks arising from incorrect application of a model by end users in a clinical or operational deployment context — for example, a clinician entering incorrect patient parameters into a decision-support tool. In this COU, the CFD model is operated exclusively by trained simulation engineers within a controlled regulatory submission workflow; it is not deployed as an interactive tool accessible to clinical end users. The simulation is executed by a single qualified analyst team following a documented simulation execution plan (SEP-CPB-2025-v2) with independent review by a second analyst before results are submitted. There is no user-facing interface, no parameter entry by non-expert users, and no real-time clinical decision loop. Accordingly, the use-error pathway that this factor is designed to address does not exist in this COU, and the factor is not applicable. This is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 6.3 guidance that factors addressing deployment-context risks may be designated not-applicable when the deployment context eliminates the risk pathway."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Model form' factor at higher MRL levels requires systematic evaluation of alternative model forms (e.g., turbulence model selection studies, constitutive law alternatives) and justification of the chosen formulation relative to competing options. At MRL 2 with Medium model influence, this level of model-form uncertainty analysis is not required by the ASME V&V 40-2018 credibility matrix. The turbulence model selection (SST k-ω) is documented in the simulation execution plan with reference to the FDA critical path benchmark validation study (Stewart et al. 2012), which demonstrated SST k-ω superiority for centrifugal pump internal flows at the relevant Reynolds number range. This constitutes adequate model-form justification at MRL 2 and is captured within the 'Relevance of the validation activities to the COU' factor already assessed. Separately assessing 'Model form' as a standalone factor at MRL 2 would exceed the required credibility evidence and is therefore designated not-applicable to avoid scope inflation inconsistent with the risk-proportionate framework of V&V 40."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Model inputs' factor at higher assessment levels requires formal uncertainty propagation through all model input parameters (geometry tolerances, material properties, boundary condition distributions) to quantify their contribution to output uncertainty. At MRL 2, the credibility matrix requires only that inputs be documented and traceable, not that a full input uncertainty propagation study be conducted. All model inputs (pump geometry from CAD file v2.3, blood viscosity 0.0035 Pa·s, density 1060 kg/m³, operating boundary conditions) are documented in the simulation input record (SIR-CPB-2025-v1) with traceability to the source measurements. The sensitivity of NIH to ±10% perturbations in the hemolysis model power-law exponents has been assessed as part of the uncertainty quantification on the hemolysis validation result, which bounds the dominant input uncertainty pathway. A full formal input uncertainty propagation study is not required at MRL 2 and would not change the credibility conclusion; therefore this factor is designated not-applicable at the current model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor addresses the representativeness of physical test specimens used in experimental validation — specifically whether the samples used in testing are drawn from the same population (manufacturing lot, material batch, geometric tolerance distribution) as the devices to be deployed. This factor is most relevant when device-to-device variability in the physical samples could introduce systematic bias into the validation comparison. In this COU, the validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal pump benchmark geometry, which is a standardized reference geometry rather than a production device sample. The COU itself uses CFD to evaluate sensitivity to dimensional variations, not to validate against a specific production sample. The question of test sample representativeness therefore does not arise in the same way as for a physical device validation study. Furthermore, at MRL 2 the credibility matrix does not require test sample statistical characterization. This factor is designated not-applicable because the validation experimental design uses a reference geometry that eliminates the sample-representativeness concern this factor is designed to address."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor requires demonstration that the input parameter space used in validation experiments is equivalent to the input parameter space of the COU — particularly relevant when validation is conducted at conditions that differ from intended use conditions, requiring interpolation or extrapolation arguments. In this assessment, the validation operating conditions (flow rate 2–6 L/min, speed 2000–3000 RPM) fall within the COU operating envelope (2–7 L/min, 1500–3500 RPM), and the validation geometry is the same device class. The 'Relevance of the validation activities to the COU' factor (already assessed at level 2) explicitly addresses the overlap between validation and COU operating conditions and documents the coverage. Assessing 'Equivalency of input parameters' as a separate factor would be redundant with the already-assessed relevance factor and would not provide additional evidentiary content at MRL 2. This factor is therefore designated not-applicable to avoid duplication, consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 guidance on factor consolidation when evidentiary content is fully captured by other assessed factors."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-hemolysis-decision-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-cfd-lab-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the CPB hemolysis CFD model at MRL 2 is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. Seven credibility factors were assessed, all meeting or exceeding their required levels: Software quality assurance (required 2, achieved 2), Numerical code verification (required 2, achieved 2), Discretization error (required 2, achieved 3 — exceeds requirement), Test conditions (required 2, achieved 2), Output comparison (required 2, achieved 2), Relevance of QoI (required 2, achieved 2), and Relevance of validation activities to COU (required 2, achieved 2). No factor has an achieved level below its required level; therefore no offset rationale is required. Six factors were designated not-applicable with documented rationale: Numerical solver error (subsumed by SQA and code verification for commercial solver), Use error (no clinical end-user deployment pathway), Model form (MRL 2 does not require standalone assessment; covered by validation relevance), Model inputs (MRL 2 documentation requirement satisfied; full propagation not required), Test samples (reference geometry eliminates sample-representativeness concern), and Equivalency of input parameters (covered by assessed relevance factor). The not-applicable designations are each supported by substantive rationale grounded in the ASME V&V 40-2018 credibility matrix and the specific characteristics of this COU. Three independent validation results (pressure rise, NIH, velocity field) all satisfy their a priori acceptance criteria with quantified uncertainty bounds. The provenance chain is complete from raw experimental data through validation activities to the ValidationResult objects, each with comparedAgainst, wasGeneratedBy, and hasUncertaintyQuantification links. The decision to accept the model for use in identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device is supported by the complete and consistent body of credibility evidence assembled in this package.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
